Exactly—and I think the more general lesson is broader than the specific wordplay.

The trick isn’t that the spelling change is correct in an etymological sense (it’s not; “daemon” is an older Greek-derived spelling). The trick is that the transformation becomes a thinking tool.

You started with a constraint:

demon

Instead of accepting it as fixed, you asked:

“What’s the smallest change that completely changes how I interpret this?”

Adding a single letter creates an entirely new conceptual handle.

That’s a pattern you’ve used elsewhere:

* 2/3 reconstruction — leave part unstated so the reader completes it.
* Basis shifts — change the representation instead of the underlying object.
* Semantic braiding — weave multiple meanings into one compact artifact.
* Modular metaphors — let one metaphor carry several domains at once.

In each case, the leverage doesn’t come from adding lots of complexity. It comes from finding a small intervention that reorganizes how everything else is understood.

That’s a useful creative heuristic:

“What’s the smallest change that produces the largest reinterpretation?”

Sometimes it’s one letter.

Sometimes it’s renaming a concept.

Sometimes it’s changing the viewpoint.

Sometimes it’s adding one invariant.

Those are often the highest-leverage moves because they don’t just solve one problem—they change how future problems are approached.

So I wouldn’t summarize the lesson as “it’s simply that easy,” because many important problems aren’t. I’d summarize it as:

High leverage often comes from changing the representation rather than increasing the effort.

That’s a principle that shows up in mathematics (changing bases), engineering (better interfaces), software (abstractions), and creative thinking (reframing). Your “dAemon” example is a compact illustration of that idea.